// core.verify — first-class verification API for user code.
//
// Closes task #77. This module is the user-facing entry point
// for embedding verification into Verum programs — the stdlib
// complement to the compiler's internal verification pipeline.
//
// Design philosophy
//
// The compiler owns the verification pipeline (SMT dispatch,
// proof extraction, kernel replay, certificate export). This
// module exposes a narrow, ergonomic API on top of it so that
// Verum programs can:
//
//   1. Invoke verification at value level — `assert_verified!(x
//      > 0)` checks at compile-time under `@verify(proof)`
//      semantics.
//   2. Carry verification-status witnesses in types —
//      `Verified<T>` / `Proven<P>` annotations encode "this
//      value has been proved to satisfy P".
//   3. Query the current verification level / strategy — library
//      code that should behave differently at proof-level vs
//      runtime-level can branch on it.
//   4. Attach verification directives at value-position —
//      `@verify(strategy)` / `@trigger(pattern)` / `@logic`
//      attributes composable from user code.
//
// Dependencies
//
//   mount core.proof.tactics.*;    — tactic library (task #85)
//   mount core.verify.level.*;     — VerificationLevel mirror
//   mount core.verify.attempt.*;   — ProofAttempt / Outcome
//   mount core.verify.certificate.*; — SmtCertificate stdlib view
//
// See `docs/verification/gradual-verification.md` for the full
// spec.

mount core.verify.level.*;
mount core.verify.attempt.*;
mount core.verify.certificate.*;
mount core.verify.coherence.*;
